{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17477877","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17477877"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T23:07:39+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T23:07:39+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14907"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14907","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14907"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.62,0.05,0.18,0.04,0.11]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7598"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"59301"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7598","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7598"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14907"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"44712"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"39"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"88"},{"type":"tags","id":"659"},{"type":"tags","id":"1061"},{"type":"tags","id":"2316"},{"type":"tags","id":"3484"},{"type":"tags","id":"3485"},{"type":"tags","id":"4174"},{"type":"tags","id":"8118"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"18595"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"59301","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/59301"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA nine-month-old boy presents to the Emergency Department with his third episode of pneumonia in three months. He has also had two episodes of otitis media requiring antibiotics. He was well for the first six months of life. He has no other medical history and takes no regular medications. He was born at term following an uncomplicated pregnancy and delivery. His immunisations are up to date. His parent mentions that a maternal uncle died in early childhood from recurrent infections.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears unwell. His pulse rate is 140/min, respiratory rate 45/min, SpO2 92% on room air, and temperature 38.5\u00b0C. There are decreased breath sounds and crackles in the right lower zone. Notably, his tonsils are small and lymph nodes are difficult to palpate. A chest X-ray shows right lower lobe consolidation.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following investigation findings would be most likely in this patient?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Normal T cells with absent B cells","Normal T cells with high B cells","Absent T cells with normal B cells","High T cells with normal B cells","Low T cells with high B cells"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis case presents classic features of X-linked agammaglobulinaemia (XLA), including recurrent bacterial infections starting after 6 months of age (when maternal antibodies decline), male sex, family history suggesting X-linked inheritance, and small lymphoid tissue. The timing is particularly characteristic - patients are protected by maternal antibodies for the first 4-6 months of life, after which they develop recurrent bacterial infections.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENormal T cells with absent B cells\u003C/strong\u003E is the characteristic finding in XLA. The condition is caused by mutations in the Bruton tyrosine kinase (BTK) gene, which is essential for B cell development. This results in a complete or near-complete absence of B cells, while T cell numbers and function remain normal.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAbsent T cells with normal B cells\u003C/strong\u003E would be more suggestive of severe combined immunodeficiency (SCID), which typically presents earlier in life with more severe infections including opportunistic pathogens.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELow T cells with high B cells\u003C/strong\u003E is not a pattern typically seen in primary immunodeficiencies. This pattern would be unusual as B cell development generally requires normal T cell function.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENormal T cells with high B cells\u003C/strong\u003E might be seen in some autoimmune conditions but would not explain this patient\u0027s presentation with recurrent bacterial infections.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHigh T cells with normal B cells\u003C/strong\u003E might be seen in acute infections but would not explain the underlying susceptibility to infection in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe diagnosis of XLA is confirmed by finding very low or absent B cells in peripheral blood, extremely low or absent immunoglobulins of all classes, and genetic testing for BTK mutations. Treatment involves regular immunoglobulin replacement therapy and prompt treatment of infections.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["X-linked agammaglobulinaemia presents with recurrent bacterial infections after 6 months of age when maternal antibodies wane.","Absence of B cells and very low immunoglobulins are diagnostic hallmarks of agammaglobulinaemia.","Regular immunoglobulin replacement therapy prevents infections in patients with agammaglobulinaemia."],"references":["Smith T, Cunningham-Rundles C. Primary B-cell immunodeficiencies. Hum Immunol. 2019 Jun;80(6):351-362. doi: 10.1016/j.humimm.2018.10.015. Epub 2018 Oct 22. PMID: 30359632; PMCID: PMC7395616."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"44712"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14907"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"44712","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/44712"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-06T19:15:13+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-06T19:15:57+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7598"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"59301"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"9","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/9"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc76","name":"Paediatrics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-01-16T08:39:03+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"39","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/39"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udee1\ufe0f","name":"Immunology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:44+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"76","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/76"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level II","synonyms":null,"description":"Understand (interpreting and summarizing information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGro